observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE instruct the (a) Municipal Treasurer to 
(i) expedite the updating of taxpayers’ index card in order to provide the Accounting Office an updated Certified List of Taxpayers and Tax Due as the basis in setting-up of RPT/SET receivables in the books of accounts at the beginning of the year; 
(ii) in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, study the viability of computerization of RPT records for efficient management of real property operations; and
(iii) employ effective collection strategies by updating and posting the notice of delinquency for property taxes at designated areas and conduct massive campaign and public information dissemination on the value of paying taxes; and if warranted, enforce the provision of Section 254(b) of the RA 7160 in the collection of delinquent taxes; 
(b) OIC-Municipal Accountant to use the Certified List of Taxpayers and Tax Due as the basis in recording the RPT/SET tax receivables at the beginning of the year; and (c) OIC-Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records of RPT/SET receivables in order to report reliably the said accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that the LCE direct the 
(a) Municipal Engineer to prepare an updated or reconstruct the actual structure lay out plan of the public market; 
(b) Municipal Treasurer and the designated Market Administrator 
(i) require stallholders to execute updated and valid contracts in accordance with the recently approved Municipal Market ordinance; 


(ii) to issue the necessary follow-up/demand letters to the delinquent stall owners/occupants for the settlement of their over-due obligations or initiate legal action, if warranted, to collect said arrearages; 
(iii) require the stall owners to observe faithful compliance of their duties and obligations as stated in the executed agreement and penalize them in case of any breach or violation stipulated thereto, particularly on the prohibited sub-leasing of stalls; 
(iv) submit an updated master list of stall owners and reconcile the same with the actual occupants and numbers of market stalls appearing in the updated MEO’s structure layout plan; 
(v) enforce revocation or cancellation of lease of stalls of delinquent tenants who failed to pay the market fees for more than two months as stipulated in the agreement; and 
(vi) conduct publication of offering to avoid idleness of stalls.

Due to the foregoing, we reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the Local Chief Executive require the 
(a) Bids and Awards Committee and Technical Working Group to 
(i) submit the copies of lacking documentary requirements for the above procurements; and (ii) henceforth, ensure compliance with the pertinent provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its IRR and COA Circular No. 2012-001 in all procurements through public bidding; 
(b) OIC-Municipal Accountant to strengthen her review function on the requisite documentation of procurements; 
(c) Municipal Engineer to closely monitor/supervise project implementation to ensure completion within the contract time for the immediate utilization of the intended beneficiaries; and 
(d) LDC through the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to ascertain the viability of each planned project to maximize fund utilization for the benefit of its intended users.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 
(a) continue its efforts to fully utilize the funds transferred by National Government Agencies (NGAs) for the implementation of various PPAs; 
(b) direct the Municipal Engineer to compute for liquidated damages, if any, in coordination with the Accounting Unit, of every project with unjustified delay in the completion and charge the amount to the respective claims of the contractors concerned accordingly; 
(c) OIC-Municipal Accountant to record fund transfers of NGAs to Due to NGAs account instead of Other Payables account; and 
(d) require the Heads of the Offices concerned to strictly observe the time frame of scheduled implementation/completion of the projects to ensure efficient delivery of public services to the intended beneficiaries.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the LCE direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer and OIC – Municipal Accountant to 
(a) ensure completion of documentary requirements prior to payments of Disbursement Vouchers; 
(b) exert efforts and strategize effective measures on how to minimize, if not eliminate the incurrence of delays in the submission of accounts; and (c) cause the immediate submission of untransmitted CY 2022 accounts, records and reports to the Audit Team.

We reiterated that the GFPS (a) continue its efforts to improve gender mainstreaming to achieve full compliance with the provisions of relevant laws and regulations; 
(b) ensure the complete implementation of activities indicated in the GPB to maximize the intervention in addressing gender-issues in the Municipality; 


(c) employ the HGDG in the attribution of costs of regular program/project to GAD; and 
(d) nominate members for seminars/trainings on gender analysis to familiarize themselves with the process and employment of HGDG in the attribution of costs of regular program/project to GAD.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Accountant who agreed to: 

(a) submit the lacking documents to facilitate the determination of the regularity of expenses; 

(b) ensure completeness of supporting documents before signing the certification (Box A) in the disbursement voucher; 

(c) collect from the concerned sellers the withholding taxes of P24,810.00 and remit the same to the BIR; 

(d) explain why withholding tax was not deducted from the payment for the procured cattles; and 

(e) explain why cattles were recognized as expense instead of the inventory.
